column3: Install Simulink Real-Time Software Updates
column5:
The general procedure for updating Simulink®
            Real-Time™ is:

column3: Install Simulink Real-Time Software Updates
column5: Navigate to the MathWorks® download page:

column3: Install Simulink Real-Time Software Updates
column5: www.mathworks.com/downloads

column3: Install Simulink Real-Time Software Updates
column5:
Navigate to the page for the Simulink
            Real-Time software version that you want. Download the software version to
                    your development computer.

column3: Install Simulink Real-Time Software Updates
column5: Install and integrate the new release software.

column3: Install Simulink Real-Time Software Updates
column5:
After updating Simulink
            Real-Time, to re-create your Simulink
            Real-Time target settings:

column3: Install Simulink Real-Time Software Updates
column5: In the MATLAB® Command Window, type slrtExplorer.

column3: Install Simulink Real-Time Software Updates
column5:
On the Targets Tree pane, select a
                    target computer
                    node.

column3: Install Simulink Real-Time Software Updates
column5: Click the Target Configuration tab.

column3: Install Simulink Real-Time Software Updates
column5:
Click Change IP Address and select the IP Address and
                    Netmask for communication method between your development and
                    target computer. For more
                    information, see Target Computer Settings. Click
                        OK.

column3: Install Simulink Real-Time Software Updates
column5:
Click the Disconnected link, toggling it to
                        Connected.

column3: Install Simulink Real-Time Software Updates
column5:
Repeat steps 2 through 5 for each
                    target computer.

column3: Install Simulink Real-Time Software Updates
column5:
Build each model that you want to execute. In the
                        Simulink Editor, on the Real-Time tab, click
                        Run on Target.

                        SLRT Explorer.

column3: Install Simulink Real-Time Software Updates
column8:

                    target computer
                    node.

column3: Install Simulink Real-Time Software Updates
column8:
To add a node representing another
                            target computer,
                            in the Targets pane, click the Add
                                target button.

column3: Install Simulink Real-Time Software Updates
column8:
To remove a node representing a
                            target computer,
                            select the node and click the Remove target
                            button.

column3: Install Simulink Real-Time Software Updates
column8:
To connect to a
                            target computer,
                            toggle the Disconnected indicator to
                                Connected.

column3: Install Simulink Real-Time Software Updates
column8:
If not previously configured, select the Target
                        Configuration tab and set the
                    target computer IP address
                    for the target computer
                    definition by using the Change IP Address button. For
                    example, Speedgoat target machines are preconfigured to IP address
                        192.168.7.5 and subnet mask
                        255.255.255.0.

column3: Troubleshoot Gaps in Streamed Data
column5: Troubleshoot Gaps in Streamed Data

column3: Troubleshoot Gaps in Streamed Data
column5:
A real-time application is producing a live streaming overload while attempting to stream
        signal data at a high rate.

column3: Troubleshoot Gaps in Streamed Data
column5: What This Issue Means

column3: Troubleshoot Gaps in Streamed Data
column5:
Live streaming from a real-time application does not guarantee all the data appears in
            the Simulation Data Inspector. Live stream instrumentation runs at a lower priority than
            the real-time application. So, data sent by live streaming could be dropped if the
            development computer to Speedgoat® target computer connection cannot keep up.

column3: Troubleshoot Gaps in Streamed Data
column5:
If a live stream overload occurs, you could see noticeable gaps in the data in the
            Simulation Data Inspector or see that some time steps are lost when you export data from
            the Simulation Data Inspector.

column3: Troubleshoot Gaps in Streamed Data
column5: Try This Workaround

column3: Troubleshoot Gaps in Streamed Data
column5: The issue is caused by high data rates and live streaming of data.

column3: Troubleshoot Gaps in Streamed Data
column5: To workaround the issue:

column3: Troubleshoot Gaps in Streamed Data
column5:
Modify the real-time application to decrease the data rate for live streaming
                    data. To do this, you could increase the sample rate, instrument fewer signals,
                    or increase the decimation of instrumented signals.

column3: Troubleshoot Gaps in Streamed Data
column5:
Change the real-time application to use file logging instead of live
                    streaming. File logging is capable of logging higher data rates without dropping
                    data.

column3: Troubleshoot Gaps in Streamed Data

column8: Tip

column6: Log or Stream Real-Time Signals by Using the Simulation Data Inspector
column8:
Consider whether to configure the Logging sample time
                     in the Instrumentation Properties for the logged signal. Use this property
                     to set a lower sample time for signals that go into the Simulation Data
                     Inspector while the simulation is running. Configuring this property can help
                     makes the Simulation Data Inspector more responsive and easier to use.

                     Log block. The Decimation value is 1.

column6: Log or Stream Real-Time Signals by Using the Simulation Data Inspector
column9: Log or Stream Real-Time Signals by Using the Simulation Data Inspector

column3: Troubleshoot Gaps in Streamed Data
column6: Log or Stream Real-Time Signals by Using the Simulation Data Inspector
column9:
With the Simulation Data Inspector and Simulink®
            Real-Time™, you can send real-time signal data directly to the Simulation Data Inspector
         or by logging signal data by recording it through a File Log
         block. If streaming signal data directly, you view the output in real time as the
         application produces it.

column3: Troubleshoot Gaps in Streamed Data
column6: Log or Stream Real-Time Signals by Using the Simulation Data Inspector
column9:
The application can produce more data than the Speedgoat® target computer can
         transmit in real time to the MATLAB® development computer. Data accumulates in the network buffer, and, if the
         buffer fills up, the RTOS drops data points. Streaming signal data directly does not
         support decimation or limit data points.

column3: Troubleshoot Gaps in Streamed Data
column6: Log or Stream Real-Time Signals by Using the Simulation Data Inspector
column9:
To avoid dropped data points caused by network buffer overruns, you can use logging
         through a File Log
         block. When logging, you connect signals to File Log
         blocks in the model. In the real-time application, these blocks store data for the buffered
         signals on the target computer. At
         the end of execution, the real-time application transmits the data to the development
         computer for display in the Simulation Data Inspector. You can then view the most important
         signals immediately and view the buffered signals afterward.

column3: Troubleshoot Gaps in Streamed Data
column6: Log or Stream Real-Time Signals by Using the Simulation Data Inspector
column9:
Logging signal data through a File Log
         block supports decimation or limit data points and supports conditional block execution
         semantics. Some examples are logging signal data by enabling data logging for a signal
         inside a for-iterator, function-call, or enabled/triggered subsystem. For more information,
         see Simulation Data
            Inspector and Real-Time Signal Logging is Affected by How Application is Run.

column6: Real-Time Signal Logging and Parameter Tuning
column8: This example shows how to use real-time signal logging and parameter tuning with Simulink® Real-Time™. After the example builds the model and downloads the real-time application, slrt_ex_param_tuning, to the target computer, the example executes multiple runs and tunes the gain 'Gain1/Gain' parameter before each run. column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5:
Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time
        Application

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5:
Some issue is producing a CPU overload when executing a real-time
        application.

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5: What This Issue Means

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5:
A CPU overload indicates that the CPU is unable to complete processing a model time
            step before restarting for the next time step.

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5:
When this error occurs, the Simulink Real-Time RTOS halts model execution and the
                Target
            object property TargetStatus shows an error, for example:

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5: mCPUOverload: Sub-rate exception: Overload limit (0) exceeded in 0.02s rate with 1 overloads

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5:
If you allow the overload, model execution continues until the allowed overload limit
            is reached. If the model continues to run after a CPU overload, the time step lasts as
            long as the time required to finish the execution. This behavior delays the next time
            step.

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5:
Model design or Speedgoat® target computer
            resources cause CPU overloads. Possible reasons are:

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5:
The target computer is
                    too slow or the model sample time is too small.

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5: The model is too complex (algorithmic complexity).

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5:
I/O latency, where each I/O channel used introduces latency into the system.
                    I/O latency can cause the execution time to exceed the model time step.

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5: To find latency values for Speedgoat boards, see www.speedgoat.com and select Products & Services > Services.

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5: Products & Services

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5: Services

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5: Try This Workaround

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5:
The Simulink®
            Real-Time™ RTOS usually halts model execution when it encounters a CPU overload. You
            can configure the Simulink
            Real-Time model to allow CPU overloads. Use this capability to support long
            initializations and for overload diagnosis. You also can try to reduce overloads by
            improving application performance and enabling the Compile with GCC
                -ffast-math option.

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5: Permit Long Initialization Time

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5:
For some real-time
                applications, normal
                initialization can extend beyond the first sample time. Use the SLRT
                    Overload Options block to increase the number of startup time steps to
                ignore overloads. By default, only the first time step ignores overloads.

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5: Note

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5:
Allowing the
    target computer CPU to overload can cause
    incorrect results, especially for multirate models. Use the SLRT Overload
        Options block only for diagnosis. When your diagnosis is complete, turn off these
    options.

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5: Enable Compile with GCC -ffast-math Option

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5:
The Compile with
                    GCC -ffast-math option enables the GCC compiler
                    -ffast-math option when compiling real-time application code.
                This option is disabled by default for Simulink
            Real-Time models.

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5:
By enabling the Compile with
                    GCC -ffast-math option, you provide the compiler with more
                flexibility to optimize floating-point math at the expense of deviating from the
                IEEE-754 floating-point standard.

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5:
For more information about the -ffast-math option, see the
                    Semantics of
                    Floating-Point Math in GCC and gcc.gnu.org/wiki/FloatingPointMath/.

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5: Force Polling Mode

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5:
The Force
                    polling mode option enables polling mode — instead of
                interrupt-driven mode — for clocking the real-time application. Enabling this option
                can help reduce CPU overloads if:

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5: The target computer has at least four CPU cores.

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5: The CPU overload is caused by sporadic TET spikes.

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column5:
Compile with GCC
                -ffast-math

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column8: Target Computer CPU Overload

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column9: Target Computer CPU Overload

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column9:
Sometimes a real-time
               application running on the
                    Speedgoat® target computer
               does not have enough time to complete processing before the next time step. This
               condition is called a CPU overload. An overload is registered every time an execution
               step is triggered while the previous step is running.

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column9:
SLRT
                         Overload Options

column3: Troubleshoot Overloaded CPU from Executing Real-Time Application
column8: The SLRT Overload Options block outputs the current CPU overload count for the identified sample rate.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column5: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column5:
I want some recommended methods to improve unsatisfactory real-time
        application
        performance.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column5: What This Issue Means

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column5:
Run-time performance and reduce the task execution
            time (TET) of a model depend on model design, Speedgoat® target computer
            capacity, and target computer
            utilization.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column5: Try This Workaround

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column5:
You can improve run-time performance and reduce the
            task execution time (TET) of a model with these methods.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column5: Enable Compile with GCC -ffast-math Option

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column5:
The Compile with
                    GCC -ffast-math option enables the GCC compiler
                    -ffast-math option when compiling real-time application code.
                This option is disabled by default for Simulink®
            Real-Time™ models.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column5:
By enabling the Compile with
                    GCC -ffast-math option, you provide the compiler with more
                flexibility to optimize floating-point math at the expense of deviating from the
                IEEE-754 floating-point standard.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column5:
Compile with
                    GCC -ffast-math

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column5:
For more information about the -ffast-math option, see the
                    Semantics of
                    Floating-Point Math in GCC and gcc.gnu.org/wiki/FloatingPointMath/.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column5: Run Performance Tools

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column5: Use these performance tools:

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column5:
To profile execution of a real-time application , use the startProfiler
                        command.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column5:
To run the profiler and plot the results, use the plot
                        function.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column5: For more information, see Execution Profiling for Real-Time Applications.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column5: Customize Concurrent Execution on Multicore                 Target Computer

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column5:
You can improve run-time performance by
                configuring your model to take advantage of your multicore
                target computer:

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column5:
Partition the model into subsystems according to the physical requirements
                        of the system that you are modeling. Set the block sample rates within each
                        subsystem to the slowest rate that meets the physical requirements of the
                        system.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column5:
Create execution tasks and triggers, and then explicitly assign subsystem
                        partitions to the tasks. See Partition Your Model Using Explicit Partitioning and Multicore Programming with Simulink.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column5:
You can also use the Simulink Schedule Editor to partition the model. In the Simulink
                        Editor, click the Modeling tab and select Design > Schedule Editor. For more information, see Create Partitions from a Rate-Based Model.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column5:
Run the real-time
                        application.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column5: Note

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column5:
Do not use MATLAB System blocks in the top
                    level of Simulink Real-Time models in which task execution is explicitly
                    partitioned. These blocks generate a TLC error when building the real-time
                    application, for example:

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column5: "Unable to find TLCBlockSID within the Block scope"

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance

column8: Execution Modes for Real-Time Applications

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column8:
Interrupt mode — The scheduler implements real-time single-tasking and
                    multitasking execution of single-rate or multirate systems, including
                    asynchronous events (interrupts). You can interact with the Speedgoat® target
                    computer while the real-time
                    application is executing
                    at high sample rates. To use this real-time mode:

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column8:
Leave the Force polling mode configuration
                            parameter disabled (default).

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column8:
Leave the pollingThreshold application option at
                            the default value.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column8:
Polling mode — The RTOS executes real-time
                    applications at sample
                    times close to the limit of the CPU. Using polling mode with high-speed and
                    low-latency I/O boards and drivers enables you to achieve real-time
                    application sample times
                    that you cannot achieve by using interrupt mode. Because polling mode disables
                    interrupts on the processor core where the model runs, it imposes restrictions
                    on the model architecture and on target communication. The base rate of the
                    real-time application is always running when executing in polling mode. To use
                    this real-time mode, either:

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column8:
Enable the Force polling mode configuration
                            parameter.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column8:
Set the pollingThreshold application option sample
                            time value to a rate below the base rate of the model.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9: Execution Modes for Real-Time Applications

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9:
The Simulink®
            Real-Time™ RTOS has two mutually exclusive execution modes.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9:
Interrupt mode — The scheduler implements real-time single-tasking and
                    multitasking execution of single-rate or multirate systems, including
                    asynchronous events (interrupts). You can interact with the Speedgoat® target
                    computer while the real-time
                    application is executing
                    at high sample rates. To use this real-time mode:

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9:
Leave the Force polling mode configuration
                            parameter disabled (default).

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9:
Leave the pollingThreshold application option at
                            the default value.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9:
Polling mode — The RTOS executes real-time
                    applications at sample
                    times close to the limit of the CPU. Using polling mode with high-speed and
                    low-latency I/O boards and drivers enables you to achieve real-time
                    application sample times
                    that you cannot achieve by using interrupt mode. Because polling mode disables
                    interrupts on the processor core where the model runs, it imposes restrictions
                    on the model architecture and on target communication. The base rate of the
                    real-time application is always running when executing in polling mode. To use
                    this real-time mode, either:

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9:
Enable the Force polling mode configuration
                            parameter.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9:
Set the pollingThreshold application option sample
                            time value to a rate below the base rate of the model.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9:
For more information, see Force polling
                mode and Application.

column9: Partitioning a Model

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column6: Create Partitions from a Rate-Based Model
column9:
Partitions are components of a model that execute independently as atomic tasks. In
        multi-tasking models, partitions are created from model components. Periodic partitions are
        scheduled as a function of sample times in a model. In export-function models, the root
        function-call inputs are defined as partitions. These partitions have a schedule associated
        with them, which tells what order the partitions execute.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column6: Create Partitions from a Rate-Based Model
column9:
With partitions, you can separate parts of the model which you can explicitly control.
        You can think of periodic partitions as components that run at specific rates in a model.
        Aperiodic partitions are components that run at specified hit times or specified events. The
        schedule of these partitions have an impact on simulation and code generation.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column6: Create Partitions from a Rate-Based Model
column9:
The Schedule Editor enables you to partition the model and interact with those
        partitions. The Schedule Editor shows partitions, the connections between them, and the
        order of the partitions.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column6: Create Partitions from a Rate-Based Model
column9: There are three types of partitions:

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column6: Create Partitions from a Rate-Based Model
column9:
The blocks running at the base rate in the model is shown as an implicit partition in
        the Schedule Editor. The base rate is the fastest discrete rate in the model.
          D1 denotes the base rate. D1 annotation also
        appears in the Timing Legend. The D1 partition or implicit partition
        always remains the first discrete partition in the order.

column9:
As a best practice, enable the Automatically handle rate
          transition for data transfer setting in the Solver
        pane. When you check Automatically handle rate transition for data
          transfer, Simulink inserts Rate Transition blocks between blocks when rate transitions are
        detected. Simulink handles rate transitions for asynchronous and periodic tasks. Simulink adds the hidden blocks configured to ensure data integrity and determinism for
        data transfers. When you check Treat each discrete rate as a separate
          task, Simulink selects multitasking execution for models operating at different rates. It
        also specifies that groups of blocks with the same execution priority are processed through
        each stage of simulation (for example, calculating output and updating states) based on task
        priority.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9: Multicore Programming with Simulink

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9:
Using the process of partitioning, mapping, and profiling in Simulink®, you can address common challenges of designing systems for concurrent
      execution.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9:
Partitioning enables you to designate regions of your model as tasks, independent of the
      details of the embedded multicore processing hardware. This independence enables you to
      arrange the content and hierarchy of your model to best suit the needs of your
      application.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9:
In a partitioned system, mapping enables you to assign partitions to processing elements
      in your embedded processing system. Use the Simulink mapping tool to represent and manage the details of executing threads, HDL code
      on FPGAs, and the work that these threads or FPGAs perform. While creating your model, you do
      not need to track the partitions or data transfer between them because the tool does this
      work. Also, you can reuse your model across multiple architectures.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9:
Profiling simulates deployment of your application under typical computational loads. It
      enables you to determine the partitioning and mapping for your model that gives the best
      performance, before you deploy to your hardware.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9:
Simulink tries to optimize the host computer performance regardless of the modeling
      method you use. For more information on the ways that Simulink helps you to improve performance, see Optimize Performance.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9: How Simulink Helps You to Overcome Challenges in Multicore Programming

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9:
Manually programming your application for concurrent execution poses challenges beyond
        the typical challenges with manual coding. With Simulink, you can overcome the challenges of portability across multiple architectures,
        efficiency of deployment for an architecture, and cyclic data dependencies between
        application components. For more information on these challenges, see Challenges in Multicore Programming.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9: Portability

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9:
Simulink enables you to determine the content and hierarchical needs of the modeled
          system without considering the target system. While creating model content, you do not
          need to keep track of the number of cores in your target system. Instead, you select the
          partitioning methods that enable you to create model content. Simulink generates code for the architecture you specify.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9:
You can select an architecture from the available supported architectures or add a
          custom architecture. When you change your architecture, Simulink generates only the code that needs to change for the second architecture.
          The new architecture reuses blocks and functions. For more information, see Supported Targets for Multicore Programming and Specify a Target Architecture.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9: Deployment Efficiency

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9:
To improve the performance of the deployed application, Simulink allows you to simulate it under typical computational loads and try multiple
          configurations of partitioning and mapping the application. Simulink compares the performance of each of these configurations to provide the
          optimal configuration for deployment. This is known as profiling. Profiling helps you to
          determine the optimum partition configuration before you deploy your system to the desired
          hardware.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9:
You can create a mapping for your application in which Simulink maps the application components across different processing nodes. You can
          also manually assign components to processing nodes. For any mapping, you can see the data
          dependencies between components and remap accordingly. You can also introduce and remove
          data dependencies between different components.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9: Cyclic Data Dependency

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9:
Some tasks of a system depend on the output of other tasks. The data dependency
          between tasks determines their processing order. Two or more partitions containing data
          dependencies in a cycle creates a data dependency loop, also known as an
            algebraic loop. Simulink does not allow algebraic loops to occur across potentially parallel
          partitions because of the high cost of solving the loop using parallel algorithms.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9:
In some cases, the algebraic loop is artificial. For example, you can have an
          artificial algebraic loop because of Model-block-based partitioning. An algebraic loop
          involving Model blocks is artificial if removing the use of Model partitioning eliminates
          the loop. You can minimize the occurrence of artificial loops. In the Configuration
          Parameter dialog boxes for the models involved in the algebraic loop, select Model Referencing > Minimize algebraic loop occurrences.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9:
Ensuring deterministic delay for periodic signals can also help break algebraic loops.
          To configure this setting, open Model Settings>
            Solver
          > Additional parameters
           > Configure Tasks. In the Data Transfer
          pane, set the default option for Periodic Signals to
            Ensure deterministic transfer (maximum delay).

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9:
Additionally, if the model is configured for the Generic Real-Time target
            (grt.tlc) or the Embedded Real-Time target
            (ert.tlc) in the Configuration Parameters dialog box, clear the
            Single output/update function check box.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9:
If the algebraic loop is a true algebraic condition, you must either contain all the
          blocks in the loop in one Model partition, or eliminate the loop by
          introducing a delay element in the loop.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column9:
The following examples show how to implement different types of parallelism in
              Simulink. These examples contain models that are partitioned and mapped to a simple
            architecture with one CPU and one FPGA.

column3: Troubleshoot Unsatisfactory Real-Time Performance
column6: Partition Your Model Using Explicit Partitioning
column8:
System tasks allow you to perform mapping incrementally. If only one periodic
              trigger is present, Simulink assigns any Model blocks, subsystem blocks, or
                MATLAB System blocks that you have not
              explicitly mapped to a task, trigger, or hardware node to a task created by the
              system. Simulink creates at most one system task for each rate in the model. If multiple
              periodic triggers are created, explicitly map the Model block
              partitions, subsystems, or MATLAB System blocks to a task, trigger, or
              hardware node.

column9:
When you have a model that is configured for concurrent execution, you can add tasks,
      create partitions, and map individual tasks to partitions using explicit partitioning. This
      enables you to execute different parts of your model to different parts of your architecture.
      For more information, see Implicit and Explicit Partitioning of Models.

column3: Troubleshoot Signals for Streaming or File Logging
column5:
There are signals selected for streaming or connected to File Log
        blocks in a model that generate an error that includes the text:

column3: Troubleshoot Signals for Streaming or File Logging
column5: Unable stream signal signal_name.

column3: Troubleshoot Signals for Streaming or File Logging
column5: What This Issue Means

column3: Troubleshoot Signals for Streaming or File Logging
column5:
This error message for signals selected for streaming or connected to File
                Log blocks could indicate that the signal has one or more of these
            issues:

column3: Troubleshoot Signals for Streaming or File Logging
column5: The signal is not available in application.

column3: Troubleshoot Signals for Streaming or File Logging
column5: The signal does not use globally accessible memory in application.

column3: Troubleshoot Signals for Streaming or File Logging
column5:
The signal connects to a Send/MessageSend
                    block.

column3: Troubleshoot Signals for Streaming or File Logging
column5: The signal has inherited sample time.

column3: Troubleshoot Signals for Streaming or File Logging
column5: The signal is discontiguous.

column3: Troubleshoot Signals for Streaming or File Logging
column5: Try These Workarounds

column3: Troubleshoot Signals for Streaming or File Logging
column5: The workarounds for these issues vary. Try these.

column3: Troubleshoot Signals for Streaming or File Logging
column5: Workaround for Signal Not Available

column3: Troubleshoot Signals for Streaming or File Logging
column5:
Make sure that these signal types are not being logged or streamed by name in the
                real-time application:

column3: Troubleshoot Signals for Streaming or File Logging
column5:
Virtual or bus signals (including signals from bus creator blocks and
                        virtual blocks)

column3: Troubleshoot Signals for Streaming or File Logging
column5: Signals that Simulink optimizes away

column3: Troubleshoot Signals for Streaming or File Logging
column5: Signals of complex or multiword data types

column3: Troubleshoot Signals for Streaming or File Logging
column5: Blocks without alphanumeric names

column3: Troubleshoot Signals for Streaming or File Logging
column5:
Workaround for Signal Not Global Available or Discontiguous
                    Signal

column3: Troubleshoot Signals for Streaming or File Logging
column5:
To resolve, try inserting a Signal Copy block (a Signal Conversion block in Signal
                Copy mode) into the signals that you want to stream. Log the copied signal output
                instead. If you use a Dashboard block, connect it to the output signal of the Signal
                Copy block.

column3: Troubleshoot Signals for Streaming or File Logging
column5: Workaround for Signal Connected to Message Block

column3: Troubleshoot Signals for Streaming or File Logging
column5:
To resolve, try streaming or file logging the input signal to the Send/MessageSend
                block. The output of the block (a message) cannot be streamed or logged.

column3: Troubleshoot Signals for Streaming or File Logging
column5: Workaround for Signal Has Inherited Sample Time

column3: Troubleshoot Signals for Streaming or File Logging
column5:
To resolve, change the signal sample time from inherited to a value. Signals with
                inherited sample time cannot be streamed or logged.

column5: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Send and Receive Blocks

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Send and Receive Blocks
column5:
A model uses Send and Receive blocks. It would be helpful to view signal data from the message line
        (output of send or input of receive) in the Simulation Data Inspector. Unexpected data
        appears when a message line in Simulink Real-Time Explorer is selected for streaming to the
        Simulation Data Inspector.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Send and Receive Blocks
column5: What This Issue Means

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Send and Receive Blocks
column5: There are some guidelines to data logging message line signals:

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Send and Receive Blocks
column5:
Message line signals that are marked for logging with the Simulation Data
                    Inspector display the data accurately in the Simulation Data Inspector.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Send and Receive Blocks
column5:
Message line signals that are connected to File
                        Log blocks display the data accurately in the Simulation Data
                    Inspector.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Send and Receive Blocks
column5:
Message line signals that are selected for dynamic streaming with an
                    instrument object—either by selecting the signals in Simulink Real-Time Explorer
                    or adding the signals by using the Application object API—do not
                    display the data accurately in the Simulation Data Inspector or in App Designer
                    instrument panel applications.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Send and Receive Blocks
column5: For more information about message lines, see Animate and Understand Sending and Receiving Messages.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Send and Receive Blocks
column5: Try This Workaround

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Send and Receive Blocks
column5:
To get accurate display of message line signals in the Simulation Data Inspector, mark
            the signals for data logging in the model or connect the signals to File
                Log blocks.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Send and Receive Blocks
column6: Animate and Understand Sending and Receiving Messages
column8: This example shows how to send, receive, and visualize messages. The example also shows how to use Simulation Data Inspector, Sequence Viewer, Animation, and Storage Inspector to understand how messages flow in your model.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Send and Receive Blocks
column6: Animate and Understand Sending and Receiving Messages
column8: Sine Wave — The signal source. The Sample time parameter of the block is set to 0.1.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Send and Receive Blocks
column6: Animate and Understand Sending and Receiving Messages
column8: Send — Converts data signals and send messages. The specified value for the Sample time parameter of the Sine Wave block determines the rate at which the Send block sends messages. Therefore, the Send block sends one message every 0.1 simulation time.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Send and Receive Blocks
column6: Animate and Understand Sending and Receiving Messages
column8: Queue — Stores messages. Observe the message line between the Send block and the Queue block. The default capacity of the queue is 16, which means the Queue block can store at most 16 messages. The default message sorting behavior is LIFO, which means incoming messages are sorted based on last-in-first-out policy. By default, the Overwrite the oldest element if queue is full check box is selected. When the queue is full, an incoming message overwrites the oldest message in the queue. For more information about using the Queue block, see Use a Queue Block to Manage Messages.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Send and Receive Blocks
column6: Animate and Understand Sending and Receiving Messages
column8: Receive — Receives messages and converts them to signal data. In the block, Sample time parameter is set to 0.1. The Receive block receives a message every 0.1 simulation time.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Send and Receive Blocks
column6: Animate and Understand Sending and Receiving Messages
column8: Scope — Visualizes messages received by the Receive block.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Send and Receive Blocks
column6: Animate and Understand Sending and Receiving Messages
column8: The Sine Wave block generates the sine wave signal (green).

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Send and Receive Blocks
column6: Animate and Understand Sending and Receiving Messages
column8: Every 0.1 simulation time, Send block converts the value of the signal to a message and sends it to the Queue block. Simulation Data inspector displays messages as stem plots. Observe the Simulation Data Inspector displaying sent messages (purple).

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Send and Receive Blocks
column6: Animate and Understand Sending and Receiving Messages
column8: The Queue block sends messages to the Receive block (blue).

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Send and Receive Blocks
column6: Animate and Understand Sending and Receiving Messages
column8: Receive block output is the reconstructed sine wave signal (orange).

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Send and Receive Blocks

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Send and Receive Blocks
column6: Animate and Understand Sending and Receiving Messages
column9: Send — Converts data signals and send messages. The specified value for the Sample time parameter of the Sine Wave block determines the rate at which the Send block sends messages. Therefore, the Send block sends one message every 0.1 simulation time.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Send and Receive Blocks
column6: Animate and Understand Sending and Receiving Messages
column9: Queue — Stores messages. Observe the message line between the Send block and the Queue block. The default capacity of the queue is 16, which means the Queue block can store at most 16 messages. The default message sorting behavior is LIFO, which means incoming messages are sorted based on last-in-first-out policy. By default, the Overwrite the oldest element if queue is full check box is selected. When the queue is full, an incoming message overwrites the oldest message in the queue. For more information about using the Queue block, see Use a Queue Block to Manage Messages.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Send and Receive Blocks
column6: Animate and Understand Sending and Receiving Messages
column9: Receive — Receives messages and converts them to signal data. In the block, Sample time parameter is set to 0.1. The Receive block receives a message every 0.1 simulation time.

column5: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Inport in Referenced Model in Test Harness

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Inport in Referenced Model in Test Harness
column5:
A Simulink®
            Test™ test harness is available for a Simulink
            Real-Time™ model. The model has a referenced model that contains an inport whose signal
        are marked for data logging in the Simulation Data Inspector. During testing, this error
        occurs:

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Inport in Referenced Model in Test Harness
column5:
Warning: Streaming to the SDI is not available for signal at
<sldiag objui="outport" objparam="1"
objname="{'Example_Harness1/Example', 'Example/Input'}">output
port 1</sldiag> of block '{'Example_Harness1/Example',
'Example/Input'}'. Add a SignalCopy block at that port and
instrument the SignalCopy output port.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Inport in Referenced Model in Test Harness
column5: What This Issue Means

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Inport in Referenced Model in Test Harness
column5:
It is not possible to stream signal data from the referenced model inport for logging
            from within the test harness.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Inport in Referenced Model in Test Harness
column5: Try This Workaround

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Inport in Referenced Model in Test Harness
column5:
Mark the input signals to the model block for logging. This model provides an example
            workaround. For more information, see the Simulink
            Test documentation.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Inport in Referenced Model
column5:
A model contains referenced models. The referenced models have root-inport signals that
        would be helpful to log and stream to the Simulation Data Inspector for visualization. When
        these signals are marked in the model for logging, a warning occurs in the diagnostic viewer
        when building the model:

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Inport in Referenced Model
column5:
Warning: Streaming to the SDI is not available for signal at
<sldiag objui="outport" objparam="1" objname="{'A/B',
'B/b1'}">output port 1</sldiag> of block '{'A/B', 'B/b1'}'.
Add a SignalCopy block at that port and instrument the
SignalCopy output port.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Nonvirtual Bus, Fixed-Point, and Multidimensional Signals
column5:
Some models use signals in nonvirtual buses, signals with fixed-point data types, and
        multidimensional signals that have a number of dimensions greater than two. It would be
        helpful to view signal data from these signals in the Simulation Data Inspector. The data
        for these signals is not visible when they are selected in Simulink Real-Time Explorer for
        streaming to the Simulation Data Inspector.

            fixed-point data types, and multidimensional signals that have a number of dimensions
            greater than two:

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Nonvirtual Bus, Fixed-Point, and Multidimensional Signals

                    the signal data displays in the Simulation Data Inspector.

column5:
When these signals are connected to File
                        Log blocks, the signal data displays in the Simulation Data
                    Inspector.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Nonvirtual Bus, Fixed-Point, and Multidimensional Signals
column5:
When these signals are selected for dynamic streaming with an instrument
                    object—either by selecting the signals in Simulink Real-Time Explorer or adding
                    the signals by using the Application object API, the
                    signal data does not display in the Simulation Data Inspector or in App Designer
                    instrument panel applications.

column9: Variable-Size Signal Basics

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Nonvirtual Bus, Fixed-Point, and Multidimensional Signals
column9:
A Simulink® signal can be a scalar, vector (1-D), matrix (2-D), or N-D. A Simulink variable-size signal is a signal whose size (the number of elements in a
      dimension), in addition to its values, can change during a model simulation. However, during a
      simulation, the number of dimensions cannot change. This capability allows you to model
      systems with varying resources, constraints, and environments.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Nonvirtual Bus, Fixed-Point, and Multidimensional Signals
column9: You can create variable-size signals in your Simulink model by using:

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Nonvirtual Bus, Fixed-Point, and Multidimensional Signals
column9:
Switch or Multiport Switch blocks with different input
          ports having fixed-size signals with different sizes. The output is a variable-size
          signal.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Nonvirtual Bus, Fixed-Point, and Multidimensional Signals
column9:
A Selector block with the Starting and ending indices
            (port) indexing option. The index port signal can specify different
          subregions of the input data signal which produce an output signal of variable size as the
          simulation progresses.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Nonvirtual Bus, Fixed-Point, and Multidimensional Signals
column9:
An S-Function block with the output port configured for a variable-size
          signal. The output includes not only the values but also the dimension of the
          signal.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Nonvirtual Bus, Fixed-Point, and Multidimensional Signals
column9:
A MATLAB Function block with the output configured for a variable-size
          signal.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Nonvirtual Bus, Fixed-Point, and Multidimensional Signals
column9: How Variable-Size Signals Propagate

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Nonvirtual Bus, Fixed-Point, and Multidimensional Signals
column9:
In the Simulink environment, variable-size signals can change their size during model
        execution in one of two ways:

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Nonvirtual Bus, Fixed-Point, and Multidimensional Signals
column9: At every step of model execution

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Nonvirtual Bus, Fixed-Point, and Multidimensional Signals
column9:
Various blocks in the model modify the sizes of the signals during execution of the
            output method.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Nonvirtual Bus, Fixed-Point, and Multidimensional Signals
column9:
Only during initialization of conditionally executed
              subsystems

column9:
Assume that the input signal dimension to this filter changes from 4 to 1 during
        simulation. It is ambiguous when and how the states of the Unit Delay blocks
        should adapt from 4 to 1 to continue processing the input. To ensure consistency, both
          Unit Delay blocks must change their state behavior synchronously. To
        prevent ambiguity, Simulink generally disallows blocks whose number of states depends on input signal
        sizes in contexts where signal sizes change at any point during execution.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Nonvirtual Bus, Fixed-Point, and Multidimensional Signals
column9:
In contrast, consider the same Discrete 2-Tap Filter block in a function-call subsystem.
        Assume that this subsystem is using the second way to propagate variable-size signals. In
        this case, the size of the input signal changes from 4 to 1 only at the initialization of
        the subsystem. At initialization, the subsystem resets all of its states (including the
        states of the two Unit Delay blocks) to their initial values. Resetting the
        subsystem ensures no ambiguity on the assignment of states to the input signal of the
        filter.

column9: Empty Signals

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Nonvirtual Bus, Fixed-Point, and Multidimensional Signals
column9:
An empty signal is a signal with a length of 0. For example, signals
        with size [0], [0x3], [2x0], and
          [2x0x3] are all empty signals. Simulink allows empty signals with variable-size signals and supports most element-wise
        operations. However, Simulink does not support empty signals for blocks that modify signal dimensions.
        Unsupported blocks include Reshape, Permute, and Sum along a specified dimension.

column8:
Simulink signals are mathematical, not physical, entities. The lines in
                        a block diagram represent mathematical, not physical, relationships among
                        blocks. Simulink signals do not travel along the lines that connect blocks in
                        the same way that electrical signals travel along a wire. Block diagrams do
                        not represent physical connections between blocks.

Dimensionality (one-dimensional, two-dimensional, or multidimensional

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Nonvirtual Bus, Fixed-Point, and Multidimensional Signals
column9:
In Simulink®, signals are the outputs of dynamic systems represented by blocks in
                  a Simulink diagram and by the diagram itself. The lines in a block
                        diagram represent
                  mathematical relationships among the signals defined by the block diagram. For
                  example, a line connecting the output of block A to the input of block B indicates
                  that the signal output of B depends on the signal output of A.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Nonvirtual Bus, Fixed-Point, and Multidimensional Signals
column9:
Simulink block diagrams represent signals with lines that have an arrowhead.
                  The source of the signal corresponds to the block that writes to the signal during
                  evaluation of its block methods (equations). The destinations of the signal are
                  blocks that read the signal during the evaluation of the block methods
                  (equations). The destination of signals in a model do not necessarily represent
                  the order of simulation of blocks in a model. The simulation order is determined
                  by Simulink automatically.

                        a block diagram represent mathematical, not physical, relationships among
                        blocks. Simulink signals do not travel along the lines that connect blocks in
                        the same way that electrical signals travel along a wire. Block diagrams do
                        not represent physical connections between blocks.

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Nonvirtual Bus, Fixed-Point, and Multidimensional Signals
column9:
You can create a signal by adding a source block to your model. For example, you
                  can create a signal that varies sinusoidally with time by adding an instance of
                  the Sine, Cosine block from the
                        Simulink Sources library into your model. To see a list of the blocks that
                  create signals in a model, see Sources. Alternatively, you
                  can use the Viewers and Generators Manager to
                  create signals in your model without using blocks.

column9: Signal Line Styles

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Nonvirtual Bus, Fixed-Point, and Multidimensional Signals
column9:
A Simulink model can include many different types of signals. As you
                        construct a block diagram, all signal types appear as a thin, solid line.
                        After you update the diagram or start simulation, the signals appear with
                        the specified line styles. These signal types enable you to differentiate
                        between different signal types. From all signal types, you can only
                        customize the nonscalar signal type. To learn more, see Signal Types.

column9:
To assign a fixed-point data type to a number or variable in MATLAB,
use the fi (Fixed-Point Designer) constructor.
The resulting fixed-point value is called a fi object.
 For example, the following creates fi objects a and b with
attributes shown in the display, all of which we can specify when
the variables are constructed. Note that when the FractionLength property
is not specified, it is set automatically to "best precision" for
the given word length, keeping the most-significant bits of the value.
When the WordLength property is not specified it
defaults to 16 bits.

column9: Scaled Doubles

column3: Troubleshoot Signal Data Logging from Nonvirtual Bus, Fixed-Point, and Multidimensional Signals
column6: Fixed-Point Data in MATLAB and Simulink
column9:
Scaled doubles are a hybrid between floating-point and fixed-point
numbers. Fixed-Point Designer™ stores them as doubles with the scaling,
sign, and word length information retained. For example, the storage
container for a fixed-point data type sfix16_En14 is int16.
The storage container of the equivalent scaled doubles data type, flts16_En14 is
floating-point double. Fixed-Point Designer applies
the scaling information to the stored floating-point double to obtain
the real-world value. Storing the value in a double almost always
eliminates overflow and precision issues.

column9:
A Simulink.Bus object data type must define the
			bus you want to make nonvirtual. A bus becomes nonvirtual when you select a block parameter
			such as Output as nonvirtual bus. Making the bus nonvirtual causes
			simulation and code generation to apply the structure defined by the bus
			object. When the bus is virtual, the bus object only validates the properties
			of the bus.

column3: Troubleshoot Signals Not Accessible by Name
column5:
You cannot log or stream by name these types of signals in the real-time

column3: Troubleshoot Signals Not Accessible by Name

                    blocks). For example, assume that you connect the output of a Mux

                    input signals rather than the names of the Mux output
                    signals.

                        reuse or Block reduction configuration
                    parameters.

                    corresponding input signal to the block. To access these signals, make them test
                    points.

column8: Internationalization Issues for Simulink Real-Time

column3: Troubleshoot Signals Not Accessible by Name
column9: Internationalization Issues for Simulink Real-Time

column3: Troubleshoot Signals Not Accessible by Name
column9:
Simulink®
            Real-Time™ inherits the internationalization support of the products that it works with:
        Simulink, Simulink
            Coder™, and Embedded Coder®. Signal and parameter names that include Unicode® characters are displayed as expected in Simulink
            Real-Time Explorer and at the MATLAB® command line.

column3: Troubleshoot Signals Not Accessible by Name
column9:
When you use the Simulation Data Inspector to observe signals, the non-ASCII signal names
      are displayed as expected. For example, assume that the signal with ID 1
      appears in an English-language and a Japanese-language version of the same model. In the
      English-language version, the signal label is input1 and the block path is
        block1/block2. In the Japanese-language version, the signal label is 入力1
      and the block path is ブロック1/ブロック2.

column3: Troubleshoot Signals Not Accessible by Name
column9:
Third-party code (for example, parsers for vendor configuration files) sometimes does not
      support cross-locale, cross-platform internationalization. For such code, you must give files
      and folders locale-specific names. For example, when parsing a configuration file on an
      English-locale machine, name the file and enclosing folder with English-locale-specific
      names.

column3: Troubleshoot Signals Not Accessible by Name
column9: Composite Interface Guidelines

column3: Troubleshoot Signals Not Accessible by Name
column9:
To simplify model appearance, you can group signals, messages, or conserving connections
			to create composite interfaces for model components and blocks.
			Composite interfaces reduce the number of ports on a model component and the number of lines
			in a block diagram. Elements of a composite interface retain their separate identities.

column3: Troubleshoot Signals Not Accessible by Name
column9:
Virtual buses meet most modeling requirements for composite
			interfaces, and they give you the flexibility to group different types of elements. They
			reduce line complexity and clutter in a block diagram and make it easier to change the
			interface incrementally. For example, if you must add or remove elements from a component
			interface, modifying a bus can be simpler than adding or removing ports.

column3: Troubleshoot Signals Not Accessible by Name
column9:
When you create a composite interface, such as a virtual bus, group lines based on their
			functionality. By organizing signals, messages, or connections into logical groupings, you
			reduce the likelihood of significant refactoring in the future.

column3: Troubleshoot Signals Not Accessible by Name
column9:
At component interfaces, use In Bus Element and Out Bus
				Element blocks. In Bus Element blocks let you extract bus elements by
			name at their point of use. Out Bus Element blocks let you build an output bus
			by connecting elements to multiple Out Bus Element blocks for the same output
			port.

column3: Troubleshoot Signals Not Accessible by Name
column9: To enforce the composition of a bus at an interface, use a Simulink.Bus object.

column3: Troubleshoot Signals Not Accessible by Name
column9:
To implement the bus definition as a structure in generated code or to iteratively process
			buses in a subsystem such as a for-each subsystem, consider making the virtual buses into
				nonvirtual buses.

				the model.

column3: Troubleshoot Signals Not Accessible by Name
column9:
With composite interfaces, you can simplify the block diagram by reducing the number of
				lines.

column3: Troubleshoot Signals Not Accessible by Name
column9:
Virtual buses simplify the signal lines in the block diagram based on four different
				types of functionality: sensor data, system goals, control signals, and system
				disturbances.

The components use In Bus Element and Out
					Bus Element blocks at their interface. For example, consider the contents of the
				subsystem named Controller.

Each In Bus Element and Out Bus Element block has a label
				that displays the corresponding element, for example, sensor.x1. In this
				example, sensor is the name of the port, and x1 is the
				name of the bus element. Two In Bus Element blocks select this element to

column8: Nonvirtual and Virtual Blocks

column3: Troubleshoot Signals Not Accessible by Name
column8:
Nonvirtual blocks play an active role in the simulation of a system. If you add or
					remove a nonvirtual block, you change the model behavior.

column3: Troubleshoot Signals Not Accessible by Name
column8:
Virtual blocks help organize a model graphically. While they play no active role in
					the simulation, they can affect the execution order of other blocks.

column9:
Simulink® blocks fall into two basic categories: nonvirtual blocks and virtual
			blocks.

					remove a nonvirtual block, you change the model behavior.

column5: Troubleshoot S-Function Build Upgrade for R2020b

column3: Troubleshoot S-Function Build Upgrade for R2020b
column5:
A pre-R2020b model uses S-Functions. When migrating this model to the current release,
        this S-Function related message appears in the build log:

column3: Troubleshoot S-Function Build Upgrade for R2020b
column5: undefined reference to 'C function in S-Function'

column3: Troubleshoot S-Function Build Upgrade for R2020b
column5: What This Issue Means

column3: Troubleshoot S-Function Build Upgrade for R2020b
column5:
In R2020b, the compiler for model builds changed from a Windows® compatible C compiler to the QNX® Neutrino® C++ compiler. To accommodate this change, update S-Function code for C++
            compatibility.

column3: Troubleshoot S-Function Build Upgrade for R2020b
column5: Tip

column3: Troubleshoot S-Function Build Upgrade for R2020b
column5:
Fortran S-Functions are not supported in R2020b and later releases of Simulink®
            Real-Time™.

column3: Troubleshoot S-Function Build Upgrade for R2020b
column5: Try This Workaround

column3: Troubleshoot S-Function Build Upgrade for R2020b
column5:
To update S-Function code for C++ compatibility, modify the declaration of the
            S-Function in the header file.

column3: Troubleshoot S-Function Build Upgrade for R2020b
column5: For example, update this C S-Function declaration:

column3: Troubleshoot S-Function Build Upgrade for R2020b
Troubleshoot S-Function Build Upgrade for R2020b
column5: Updated the code to this C++ S-Function declaration:

column3: Troubleshoot S-Function Build Upgrade for R2020b
Troubleshoot S-Function Build Upgrade for R2020b
column5:
Before building the updated code, remember to remove all artifacts from previous model
            builds.

column5: Troubleshoot Model Upgrade for R2020b

column3: Troubleshoot Model Upgrade for R2020b
column5:
When building a pre-R2020b Simulink Real-Time models in R2020b, build errors occur. Some
        of the blocks in the model have the label Obsolete Simulink Real-Time
            Block.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Upgrade for R2020b
column5: What This Issue Means

column3: Troubleshoot Model Upgrade for R2020b
column5:
For R2020b, you must upgrade the Simulink Real-Time model. A model Upgrade Advisor
            check is available to support this upgrade.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Upgrade for R2020b
column5: Try This Workaround

column3: Troubleshoot Model Upgrade for R2020b
column5:
To upgrade your model for Simulink Real-Time R2020b features, use this software
            upgrade process:

column3: Troubleshoot Model Upgrade for R2020b
column5: Install Simulink Real-Time and other required products.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Upgrade for R2020b
column5:
Install the Simulink Real-Time Target Support Package by using the MATLAB
                        Add-Ons menu.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Upgrade for R2020b
column5:
​Install the Speedgoat I/O Blockset. Go to the Speedgoat
                        website.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Upgrade for R2020b
column5: Upgrade the target machine software. See Troubleshoot System Upgrade for R2020b.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Upgrade for R2020b
column5: Open a R2020b or earlier Simulink Real-Time model.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Upgrade for R2020b
column5:
Run the Upgrade Advisor. On the
                        Modeling tab, select Model Advisor > Upgrade Advisor.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Upgrade for R2020b
column5:
In the Upgrade Advisor dialog box, select Check model for upgradable
                        Simulink Real-Time features. Click the Run This
                        Check button. The advisor lists the upgrades that it can apply
                    and the upgrades that require manual changes.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Upgrade for R2020b
column5:
After the check, click the Upgrade button. The advisor
                    upgrades the model by applying all nonmanual changes.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Upgrade for R2020b
column5: Apply Manual Changes

column3: Troubleshoot Model Upgrade for R2020b
column5:
When the Upgrade Advisor encounters model issues that it cannot resolve by using
                automated changes, the Upgrade Advisor reports these as Warning: Some of
                    the features require manual changes. It is a good practice to copy
                the text of these warnings and save it for reference as you apply changes to your
                model.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Upgrade for R2020b
column5: Apply Speedgoat Utilities

column3: Troubleshoot Model Upgrade for R2020b
column5:
In R2020b, Speedgoat® software provides support for configuring interrupts and
                Ethernet communications.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Upgrade for R2020b
column5:
To configure model interrupts, use a single block from the Speedgoat I/O Blockset. You can use this block for asynchronous subsystems or for triggering
                the base rate of the model. The list of available interrupt sources reflects the
                    Speedgoat I/O Blockset blocks configured in the model. For more information see the block
                documentation in speedgoatlib_utilities.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Upgrade for R2020b
column5:
To configure additional Ethernet ports on the target machine, the Speedgoat I/O Blockset provides a tool to configure these Ethernet ports. The configuration
                is specific to the target machine and reflects the labeling on the front plates of
                the target machine. For more information, in the MATLAB Command Window, type:

column3: Troubleshoot Model Upgrade for R2020b
column5: speedgoat.configureEthernet

column3: Troubleshoot Working with Persistent Variables
column5: When running the getPersistentVariables function or setPersistentVariables function, this error appears:

column3: Troubleshoot Working with Persistent Variables
column5:
Cannot parse the file that stores persistent variables from 
target computer. To clear the issue, delete all persistent 
variables on target computer. For more information, see 
Troubleshoot Working with Persistent Variables.

column3: Troubleshoot Working with Persistent Variables
column5: What This Issue Means

column3: Troubleshoot Working with Persistent Variables
column5:
This error message indicates that the file on the Speedgoat® target computer that stores the persistent variable values is corrupted or
            unreadable.

column3: Troubleshoot Working with Persistent Variables
column5: Try This Workaround

column3: Troubleshoot Working with Persistent Variables
column5:
To resolve this issue, clear the persistent variable values that are stored on the
            target computer.

column3: Troubleshoot Working with Persistent Variables
column5:
On the development computer, create a Target object tg and connect to the target
                    computer.

column3: Troubleshoot Working with Persistent Variables
column5:
tg = slrealtime;
connect(tg);

column3: Troubleshoot Working with Persistent Variables
column5:
Use the setPersistentVariables function to clear the persistent variable
                    values that are stored on the target computer.

column3: Troubleshoot Working with Persistent Variables
column5: setPersistentVariables(tg,[]);

column3: Troubleshoot Working with Persistent Variables
column5:
getPersistentVariables | setPersistentVariables | Persistent
                Variable Read | Persistent
                Variable Write

column3: Troubleshoot Working with Persistent Variables
column6: Apply Persistent Variables in Real-Time Applications
column9: In a model, you save variables on target computer whose values persist when the real-time application stops and even when the target computer is shut down by using Persistent Variable Write blocks. At real-time application start, you direct the real-time application to read these persistent variables by using Persistent Variable Read blocks.
