column3: Troubleshoot Long Build Times for Real-Time Application
column5: Troubleshoot Long Build Times for Real-Time Application

column3: Troubleshoot Long Build Times for Real-Time Application
column5:
The model build process for a Simscape™
            Multibody™ models is slow and uses an unexpected amount of memory.

column3: Troubleshoot Long Build Times for Real-Time Application
column5: What This Issue Means

column3: Troubleshoot Long Build Times for Real-Time Application
column5:
The default QNX® Neutrino® compiler switches for Simulink®
            Real-Time™ apply optimizations that lead to long build times or slow builds for some
            complex models, such as Simscape
            Multibody models.

column3: Troubleshoot Long Build Times for Real-Time Application
column5: Try This Workaround

column3: Troubleshoot Long Build Times for Real-Time Application
column5:
To improve the real-time application build speed, change the compiler switch
            selections from the default selections by adding the
                -fdisable-rtl-sched2 switch for the C/C++ compiler:

column3: Troubleshoot Long Build Times for Real-Time Application
column5:
Open your Simulink
            Real-Time model.

column3: Troubleshoot Long Build Times for Real-Time Application
column5:
In the Simulink Editor, from the Real-Time tab, select
                        Hardware Settings.

column3: Troubleshoot Long Build Times for Real-Time Application
column5: Select Code Generation > Build configuration > Specify

column3: Troubleshoot Long Build Times for Real-Time Application
column5:
Click the C Compiler options and add option
                        -fdisable-rtl-sched2.

column3: Troubleshoot Long Build Times for Real-Time Application
column5:
Click the C++ Compiler options and add option
                        -fdisable-rtl-sched2.

column3: Troubleshoot Long Build Times for Real-Time Application
column5: Click Apply and OK.

column3: Troubleshoot Long Build Times for Real-Time Application
column5: After updating the compiler options, the options appear as shown.

column3: Troubleshoot Long Build Times for Real-Time Application
column5:
If you prefer to use a programmatic approach to update these compiler switches, you
            could use this code.

column3: Troubleshoot Long Build Times for Real-Time Application
Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column5: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column5:
A build error occurs when building a model in accelerator mode or rapid accelerator mode
        when the model contains Simulink Real-Time blocks (for example, model blocks that represent
        hardware).

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column5: What This Issue Means

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column5:
Simulink Real-Time does not support accelerator mode or rapid accelerator mode
            simulation of models with blocks that represent hardware. For example, open the
                slrt_ex_serialasciitest model.

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column5: openExample('slrt_ex_serialasciitest').

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column5:
Change the Simulink mode to rapid accelerator, and run the model, Simulink displays
            this error:

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column5:
Unable to build a standalone executable to simulate the model 
'slrt_ex_serialasciitest' in rapid accelerator mode.

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column5:
This error occurs because accelerator mode and rapid accelerator mode produce compiled
            code that runs on the development computer, not on the Speedgoat® target computer. Any
            blocks that access hardware report a build error if you compile the model by using
            accelerator mode or rapid accelerator mode.

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column5: Try This Workaround

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column5: Change the simulation mode to normal mode or external mode.

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column8: Simulink Real-Time Options Pane

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column8:
In the Code
                            Generation
                         pane, in the System target file list,
                        select slrealtime.tlc or another Simulink Real-Time STF.
                        This setting generates system target code for Simulink
            Real-Time.

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column8: Note

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column8:
If you open a model that was originally saved with System
                                target file set to xpctarget.tlc, the
                            software updates the setting to slrealtime.tlc. To
                            retain the updated setting, save the updated model.

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column8:
The default values work for the generation of most real-time
                        applications. If you
                        want to customize the build of your real-time
                        application, set the
                        option parameters to suit your specifications.

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column8: How Acceleration Modes Work

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column8: Note

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column8:
The code generated by the accelerator and rapid
                                                  accelerator modes is suitable only for speeding
                                                  the simulation of your model. Use Simulink
            Coder to generate code for other
                                                  purposes.

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column9: How Acceleration Modes Work

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column9: Overview

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column9:
The accelerator and rapid accelerator modes use portions of the
                                                  Simulink®
            Coder™ product to create an executable.

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column9:
The accelerator and rapid accelerator modes replace the
                                        interpreted code normally used in Simulink simulations, shortening model run time.

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column9:
Although the acceleration modes use some Simulink
            Coder code generation technology, you do not need
                                        the Simulink
            Coder software installed to accelerate your
                                        model.

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column9: Note

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column9:
The code generated by the accelerator and rapid
                                                  accelerator modes is suitable only for speeding
                                                  the simulation of your model. Use Simulink
            Coder to generate code for other
                                                  purposes.

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column9: Normal Mode

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column9:
In normal mode, the MATLAB® technical computing environment is the
                                        foundation on which the Simulink software is built. Simulink controls the solver and model methods used
                                        during simulation. Model methods include such things as
                                        computation of model outputs. Normal mode runs in one
                                        process.

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column9: Accelerator Mode

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column9:
By default, accelerator mode uses Just-in-Time (JIT)
                                        acceleration to generate an execution engine in memory
                                        instead of generating C code or MEX files. You can also have
                                        your model fall back to the classic accelerator mode, in
                                        which Simulink generates and links code into a C-MEX
                                        S-function.

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column9:
In accelerator mode, the model methods are separate from the
                                                  Simulink software and are part of the
                                                  acceleration target code,
                                        which is used in later simulations.

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column9:
Simulink checks that the acceleration target code is up
                                        to date before reusing it. For more information, see Code Regeneration in Accelerated Models.

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column9: There are two modes of operation in accelerator mode.

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column9: Just-In-Time Accelerator Mode

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column9:
In this default mode, Simulink generates an execution engine in
                                                  memory for the top-level model only and not for
                                                  referenced models. As a result, a C compiler is
                                                  not required during simulation.

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column9:
Because the acceleration target
                                                  code is in memory, it is available for reuse as
                                                  long as the model is open. Simulink also serializes the acceleration
                                                  target code so that the model does not need
                                                  rebuilding when it is opened.

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column9: Classic Accelerator Mode

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column9:
If you want to simulate your model using the classic,
                                                  C-code generating, accelerator mode, run the
                                                  following command:

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column9: set_param(0,'GlobalUseClassicAccelMode','on');

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column9:
In this mode, Simulink generates and links code into a
                                                  shared library, which communicates with the
                                                  Simulink software. The target code executes
                                                  in the same process as MATLAB and Simulink.

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column9: Rapid Accelerator Mode

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column9:
Rapid accelerator mode creates a rapid accelerator
                                                  standalone executable from your model.
                                        This executable includes the solver and model methods, but
                                        it resides outside of MATLAB and Simulink. It uses external mode (see External Mode Communication (Simulink Coder)) to
                                        communicate with Simulink.

column3: Troubleshoot Build Error for Accelerator Mode
column9:
MATLAB and Simulink run in one process, and if a second processing
                                        core is available, the standalone executable runs
                                        there.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column5: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column5:
Some model build and runtime issues occur when linking a real-time application to static
        libraries (.a) or shared objects (.so).

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column5: What This Issue Means

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column5:
When building or running real-time an application that links to static link libraries
                (.a) or shared object libraries (.so), there
            are some considerations that help you use libraries that are compatible with the
                QNX® Neutrino® RTOS on the Speedgoat® target computer. These recommendations are helpful when troubleshooting
            library usage, including:

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects

A link to a library from QNX Neutrino RTOS that is available in the Simulink Real-Time target support
                    package

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column5: A shared object that is included in the model through an FMU block

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column5:
A custom static library or shared object that is linked to the real-time
                    application

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column5: These workarounds explore the possible issues.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column5: Link to Accessible Libraries or Objects

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column5:
When you link to a static library or shared object, the library or object must
                be:

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column5: Compatible with the QNX Neutrino RTOS

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column5: Accessible to the toolchain at build time

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column5:
Check to ensure that you have followed the guidelines for library compatibility.
                See External Code Integration of Libraries and C/C++ Code with Simulink Real-Time Models. Check that
                the toolchain can access the library at build time. Remember that the QNX Neutrino cannot process spaces in the path to files.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column5: Install Shared Objects on Target Computer

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column5:
After you build the real-time application that links to a shared object, install
                both the real-time application and the shared object on the target computer. Copy
                the shared objects to a location on the target computer where they can be found and
                loaded at runtime. The recommended locations are /lib,
                    /usr/lib, or /usr/local/lib. Root access
                is required to copy files to these locations.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column5:
Rebuild Real-Time Application When Rebuilding Static
                    Libraries

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column5:
Because linked static libraries are included in the real-time application, when
                you modify and rebuild a static library, you rebuild any real-time applications that
                include that library. After rebuilding the static library and the real-time
                application, reinstall the real-time application on the target computer.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column6: Compile Source Code for Functional Mock-up Units
column8: When you build a model that includes FMU blocks, you must compile the FMU source code by using the QNX Neutrino compiler qcc or q++. This compiler creates shared object SO files that you include in the FMU. This process makes sure that the FMU contains the code to run on a Simulink Real-Time target computer. For more information, see Apply Functional Mock-up Units by Using Simulink Real-Time.

The table provides a guide to model configuration parameters on Code Generation > Custom Code pane of the Model Configuration Parameters dialog box that support the build
      process for external code integration. For information about folders for your external code,
      see Manage Build Process Folders (Embedded Coder). If you choose to place your external code in the

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9: Preserve External Code Files in Build Folder

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
By default, the build process deletes foreign source files.
You can preserve foreign source files by following these guidelines.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
If you put a .c/.cpp or .h source
file in a build folder, and you want to prevent the code generator
from deleting it during the TLC code generation process, insert the
text target specific file in the first line of
the .c/.cpp or .h file. For
example:

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
/*  COMPANY-NAME target specific file
 *
 *   This file is created for use with the 
 *   COMPANY-NAME target.
 *   It is used for ...
 */
...

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
Make sure that you spell the text “target specific file”
as shown in the preceding example, and that the text is in the first
line of the source file. Other text can appear before or after this
text.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
Flagging user files in this manner prevents postprocessing these
files to indent them with generated source files. Auto-indenting occurred
in previous releases to build folder files with names having the pattern model_*.c/.cpp (where * was
text). The indenting is harmless, but can cause differences detected
by source control software that can potentially trigger unnecessary
updates.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9: Build Support for S-Functions

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
User-written S-Function blocks provide a powerful way to incorporate
external code into the Simulink® development environment. In most
cases, you use S-functions to integrate existing external code with
generated code. Several approaches to writing S-functions are available:

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9: Write Noninlined S-Function

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9: Write Wrapper S-Function and TLC Files

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9: Write Fully Inlined S-Functions

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9: Write Fully Inlined S-Functions with mdlRTW Routine

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9: S-Functions for Code Reuse

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9: S-Functions for Multirate Multitasking Environments

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
S-functions also provide the most flexible and capable way of
including build information for legacy and custom code files in the
build process.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
There are different ways of adding S-functions to the build
process.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9: Implicit Build Support

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
When building models with S-functions, the build process adds
rules, include paths, and source file names to the generated makefile.
The source files (.h, .c, and .cpp)
for the S-function must be in the same folder as the S-function MEX-file.
Whether using the toolchain approach or template makefile approach
for builds, the build process propagates this information through
the toolchain or template makefile.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9: .h

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9: .c

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9: .cpp

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
If the file sfcnname.h exists
in the same folder as the S-function MEX-file (for example, sfcnname.mexext),
the folder is added to the include path.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
If the file sfcnname.c or sfcnname.cpp exists
in the same folder as the S-function MEX-file, the build process adds
a makefile rule for compiling files from that folder.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
When an S-function is not inlined with a TLC file,
the build process must compile the S-function source file. To determine
the name of the source file to add to the list of files to compile,
the build process searches  for sfcnname.cpp on
the MATLAB path.  If the source file is found, the build process
adds the source file name to the makefile. If sfcnname.cpp is
not found on the path, the build process adds the file name sfcnname.c to
the makefile, whether or not it is on the MATLAB path.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9: Note

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
For the Simulink engine to find the MEX-file for simulation
and code generation, it must exist on the MATLAB path or  exist
in our current MATLAB working folder.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9: Specify Additional Source Files for an S-Function

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
If your S-function has additional source file dependencies,
you must add the names of the additional modules to the build process.
Specify the file names:

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
In the S-function modules field
in the S-Function block parameter dialog box

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
With the SFunctionModules parameter
in a call to the set_param function

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
For example, suppose you build your S-function with multiple
modules.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9: mex sfun_main.c sfun_module1.c sfun_module2.c

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
You can then add the modules to the build process by doing one
of the following:

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
In the S-function block dialog box, specify sfun_main, sfun_module1,
and sfun_module2 in the S-function modules field.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9: At the MATLAB command prompt, enter:

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9: set_param(sfun_block,'SFunctionModules','sfun_module1 sfun_module2')

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
Alternatively, you can define a variable to represent the parameter
value.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
modules = 'sfun_module1 sfun_module2'
          set_param(sfun_block,'SFunctionModules', modules)

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
The S-function modules field and SFunctionModules parameter
do not support complete source file path specifications. To use the
parameter, the code generator must find the additional source files
when executing the makefile. For the code generator to locate the
additional files, place them in the same folder as the S-function
MEX-file. You can then leverage the implicit build support described
in Implicit Build Support.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
When you are ready to generate code, force the code generator
to rebuild the top model, as described in Control Regeneration of Top Model Code.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
For more complicated S-function file dependencies, such as specifying
source files in other locations or specifying libraries or object
files, use the rtwmakecfg.m API, as described in Use rtwmakecfg.m API to Customize Generated Makefiles.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9: Use TLC Library Functions

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
If you inline your S-function by writing a TLC file, you can
add source file names to the build process by using the TLC library
function LibAddToModelSources. For details, see LibAddSourceFileCustomSection(file, builtInSection, newSection).

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9: LibAddToModelSources

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9: Note

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
This function does not support complete source file path specifications.
The function assumes that the code generator can find the additional
source files when executing the makefile.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
Another useful TLC library function is LibAddToCommonIncludes.
Use this function in a #include statement to include
S-function header files in the generated model.h header
file. For details, see LibAddToCommonIncludes(incFileName).

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
For more complicated S-function file dependencies, such as specifying
source files in other locations or specifying libraries or object
files, use the rtwmakecfg.m API, as described in Use rtwmakecfg.m API to Customize Generated Makefiles.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9: Precompile S-Function Libraries

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
You can precompile new or updated S-function libraries (MEX-files)
for a model by using the MATLAB language function rtw_precompile_libs. Using a specified model
and a library build specification, this function builds and places
the libraries in a precompiled library folder.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9: rtw_precompile_libs

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
By precompiling S-function libraries, you can optimize system
builds. Once your precompiled libraries exist, the build process can
omit library compilation from subsequent builds. For models that use
numerous libraries, the time savings for build processing can be significant.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9: To use rtw_precompile_libs:

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
Set the library file suffix, including the file type
extension, based on your system platform.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
Consider determining the type of platform, and then use the TargetLibSuffix parameter
to set the library suffix accordingly. For example, when applying
a suffix for a GRT target, you can set the suffix to _std.a for
a UNIX® platform and _vcx64.lib for a Windows® platform.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
There are a number of factors that influence the precompiled
library suffix and extension. The following table provides examples
for typical selections of system target file, the compiler toolchain,
and other options that affect your
choice of suffix and extension. For more information, examine the
template make files in the matlab/rtw/c/grt folder
or matlab/rtw/c/ert folder.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9: Set the precompiled library folder.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
Use one of the following methods to set the precompiled
library folder:

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9: Set the TargetPreCompLibLocation parameter, as described in Specify the Location of Precompiled Libraries.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
Set the makeInfo.precompile field in an rtwmakecfg.m function file.
(For more information, see Use rtwmakecfg.m API to Customize Generated Makefiles.)

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
If you set TargetPreCompLibLocation and makeInfo.precompile,
the setting for TargetPreCompLibLocation takes
precedence.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
The following command sets the precompiled library folder for
model my_model to folder lib under
the current working folder.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects

Set up a structure that defines a build specification.  The following table

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
A cell array of character vectors that name the folders
containing rtwmakecfg files for libraries to
be precompiled. The function uses the Name and Location elements
of  makeInfo.library, as returned by rtwmakecfg,
to specify the name and location of the precompiled libraries. If
you set the TargetPreCompLibLocation parameter
to specify the library folder, that setting overrides the makeInfo.library.Location setting.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column9:
Note: The specified model must contain blocks
that use precompiled libraries specified by the rtwmakecfg files
because the TMF-to-makefile conversion generates the library rules
only if the build process uses the libraries.

column3: Troubleshoot Model Links to Static Libraries or Shared Objects
column6: External Code Integration of Libraries and C/C++ Code with Simulink Real-Time Models
column9:
function makeInfo = rtwmakecfg​
proj = currentProject;​
rootPath = proj.RootFolder;​
makeInfo.linkLibsObjs = {};​
sysTarget = get_param(bdroot, 'RTWSystemTargetFile');​
switch sysTarget​
    case 'speedgoat.tlc'​
        makeInfo.includePath = '<includePath>';​
        makeInfo.linkLibsObjs{end+1} = '<libraryPath>';​
    otherwise​
        error('No rtwmakecfg found for %s target file', sysTarget);​
end​
end​

column3: Troubleshoot Folder Names with Spaces or Special Characters Halt Model Builds
column5:
For the Simulink Real-Time model build … message or for the
                Error(s) encountered while building … message, message indicates
            that a space character or special character appears in the file path. The QNX® Neutrino® toolchain for the code generation target is not compatible with file paths
            that contain spaces or special characters, the model build halts and does not output a
            real-time application.

column3: Troubleshoot Folder Names with Spaces or Special Characters Halt Model Builds
column6: Build Process Support for File and Folder Names
column9:
If the file system is ReFS (Resilient File
                    System), it is an issue. The ReFS does not provide short filename support.
                    Except for the MATLAB installation folder, the build process does not support folder
                    names with spaces for the ReFS file system. If your work environment requires
                    short filename support for the build folder or for additional external code
                    folders, do not use ReFS.

If the file system is NTFS (New Technology
                    File System), it is possible that the build error is related to a registry
                    setting incompatibility. Continue with troubleshooting steps.

column3: Troubleshoot Folder Names with Spaces or Special Characters Halt Model Builds
column6: Build Process Support for File and Folder Names

The error could stem from an issue with short filename support on a system using NTFS.
            Check the Windows registry setting that enables the creation of short names for files,
            folders, and paths.

column3: Troubleshoot System Upgrade for R2020b
column5: Troubleshoot System Upgrade for R2020b

column3: Troubleshoot System Upgrade for R2020b
column5:
After upgrading Simulink Real-Time software to R2020b and installing the Simulink
        Real-Time Target Support Package, the system cannot download real-time applications to the
        target computer.

column3: Troubleshoot System Upgrade for R2020b
column5: What This Issue Means

column3: Troubleshoot System Upgrade for R2020b
column5:
The upgrade for release R2020b requires software upgrades to the Simulink Real-Time
            software and the Speedgoat Target Machine software.

column3: Troubleshoot System Upgrade for R2020b
column5: Try This Workaround

column3: Troubleshoot System Upgrade for R2020b
column5:
In R2020b, the change to a 64-bit POSIX compliant real-time operating system on the target
        computer requires a software upgrade for your Speedgoat® real-time target machine. For this upgrade, the Speedgoat I/O Blockset provides an interactive tool. To retain compatibility with previous versions
        of MATLAB, you can choose to upgrade the target machine to a dual-boot system where you can
        select the operating system at startup. Or, you can upgrade the target machine to use only
        the new operating system. For the upgrade, you need a USB drive and the target machine needs
        a keyboard and a monitor.

column3: Troubleshoot System Upgrade for R2020b
column5: To upgrade your software:

column3: Troubleshoot System Upgrade for R2020b
column5: Install Simulink Real-Time and other required products.

column3: Troubleshoot System Upgrade for R2020b
column5:
Install the Simulink Real-Time Target Support Package by using the MATLAB
                    Add-Ons menu.

column3: Troubleshoot System Upgrade for R2020b
column5: ​Install the Speedgoat I/O Blockset. Go to the Speedgoat customer portal.

column3: Troubleshoot System Upgrade for R2020b
column5: To start the target machine upgrade, in the MATLAB Command Window, type:

column3: Troubleshoot System Upgrade for R2020b
column5: speedgoat.migrateTarget

column3: Troubleshoot System Upgrade for R2020b
column5:
For more information, go to the Speedgoat
            website.

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column5: Investigate issues that can occur when ETAS® Inca controls a real-time application.

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column5:
A third-party calibration tool (ETAS Inca) is not working with the real-time
        application.

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column5: What This Issue Means

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column5:
You can use the ETAS Inca tool to view signals and tune parameters in the real-time
            application. For more information,
            see the steps in Prepare ASAP2 Data Description File. In
            addition to the limitations listed in ETAS Inca Limitations, there are
            various issues that can prevent the operation of this tool.

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column5: Try This Workaround

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column5: For ETAS Inca tool issues, try these workarounds.

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column5: Simulation Data Inspector in Use

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column5:
Simulation Data Inspector and the third-party calibration
tools (Vector CANape® and ETAS Inca) are mutually exclusive.
If you use the Simulation Data Inspector to view signal data, you cannot use the calibration
tools. If you use the calibration tools, you cannot use the Simulation Data Inspector to view
signal data.

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column5: Client Cannot Connect

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column5:
Check the IP address of the Speedgoat® target computer
                associated with the model and compare it to the address stored in the ASAP2
                file.

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column5: ASAP2 File Out of Date

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column5:
When you rebuild a Simulink®
            Real-Time™ application, update the ASAP2 file loaded in the calibration tool with
                the new version of the file. The ASAP2 file is valid only until the next time that
                you build the application.

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column5: Cannot Disable Freeze Mode

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column5:
Remove the dataset file from the target file system and reset the parameters to
                the original values specified in your model. The dataset file is named
                        flashdata_model_name.dat.

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column5: Transport Layer Failure

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column5: When a transport layer failure occurs, ETAS Inca can display this message:

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column5: ERROR: Transport Layer Failure, Inconsistent MsgCounter

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column5:
This error appears in ETAS Inca when the incorrect setting is used for
                    'Counter Consistency Mode'. Make sure that the
                    'Counter Consistency Mode' is set to 'one counter
                    for all CTOs+DTOs' in the hardware settings for your
                experiment.

column8: Connecting MATLAB® to the target computer while using ETAS Inca.

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column8:
Loading, starting, or stopping the real-time
                    application by using
                        ETAS Inca commands.

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column8:
To load, start, or stop the real-time application on the target computer, use
                    the target computer command-line interface. For example:

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column8: slrealtime load --AppName app_name

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column8: slrealtime start

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column8: slrealtime stop

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column8: For more information, see Target Computer Command-Line Interface.

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column8: ETAS Inca flash programming.

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column8:
Multiple simultaneous ETAS Inca connections to a single
                    target computer.

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column8:
Tunability of parameters with ExportedGlobal storage class
                    when the model has other parameters with PageSwitching
                    storage class. As a work around you can:

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column8:
Place all the parameters you want to tune in model workspace.
                                Or

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column8:
Change the default mapping for storage class from
                                    PageSwitching to default.
                                The PageSwitching storage class is not used, and
                                the page switching functionality is not available.

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column8:
Every piece of data that the Simulink
            Real-Time software adds to the event list slows the real-time
                    application. The amount of
                    data that you can observe depends on the model sample time and the speed of the
                    target computer. It is
                    possible to overload the
                    target computer CPU to
                    where data integrity is reduced.

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column8:
You can trace only signals and scalar parameters. You cannot trace vector
                    parameters.

column9:
Tunability of parameters with ExportedGlobal storage class
                    when the model has other parameters with PageSwitching
                    storage class. As a work around you can:

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column9:
Place all the parameters you want to tune in model workspace.

column3: Troubleshoot ETAS Inca Operation
column9:
Change the default mapping for storage class from
                                    PageSwitching to default.
                                The PageSwitching storage class is not used, and
                                the page switching functionality is not available.

column5: Troubleshoot Vector CANape Operation

column3: Troubleshoot Vector CANape Operation
column5:
A third-party calibration tool (Vector CANape®) is not working with the real-time
        application.

column3: Troubleshoot Vector CANape Operation
column5: What This Issue Means

column3: Troubleshoot Vector CANape Operation
column5:
You can use the Vector CANape tool to view signals and tune parameters in the real-time
            application. For more information,
            see the steps in Prepare ASAP2 Data Description File. In
            addition to the limitations listed in Vector CANape Limitations, there are
            various issues that can prevent the operation of this tool.

column3: Troubleshoot Vector CANape Operation
column5: Try This Workaround

column3: Troubleshoot Vector CANape Operation
column5: For Vector CANape tool issues, try these workarounds.

column3: Troubleshoot Vector CANape Operation
column5: Simulation Data Inspector in Use

column3: Troubleshoot Vector CANape Operation
column5:
Simulation Data Inspector and the third-party calibration
tools (Vector CANape and ETAS® Inca) are mutually exclusive.
If you use the Simulation Data Inspector to view signal data, you cannot use the calibration
tools. If you use the calibration tools, you cannot use the Simulation Data Inspector to view
signal data.

column3: Troubleshoot Vector CANape Operation
column5: Client Cannot Connect

column3: Troubleshoot Vector CANape Operation
column5:
Check the IP address of the Speedgoat® target computer
                associated with the model and compare it to the address stored in the ASAP2
                file.

column3: Troubleshoot Vector CANape Operation
column5: ASAP2 File Out of Date

column3: Troubleshoot Vector CANape Operation
column5:
When you rebuild a Simulink®
            Real-Time™ application, update the ASAP2 file loaded in the calibration tool with
                the new version of the file. The ASAP2 file is valid only until the next time that
                you build the application.

column3: Troubleshoot Cannot Load Shared Object on Target Computer
column5: Troubleshoot Cannot Load Shared Object on Target Computer

column3: Troubleshoot Cannot Load Shared Object on Target Computer
column5:
When loading and running on the target computer a real-time application that depends on a
        shared object (.so), the real-time application cannot run and load the
        library. In the system log, A message like this error appears:

column3: Troubleshoot Cannot Load Shared Object on Target Computer
column5: ldd:FATAL: Could not load library xyz.so

column3: Troubleshoot Cannot Load Shared Object on Target Computer
column5: What This Issue Means

column3: Troubleshoot Cannot Load Shared Object on Target Computer
column5:
An error loading a shared object can indicate some issue with missing or corrupt
            library dependencies on the target computer. The issue could be:

column3: Troubleshoot Cannot Load Shared Object on Target Computer
column5:
The download to the Speedgoat® target computer has modified or has removed some required files on
                    the target computer.

column3: Troubleshoot Cannot Load Shared Object on Target Computer
column5:
The download to the target computer put the library in a location that is not
                    accessible when the real-time application runs.

column3: Troubleshoot Cannot Load Shared Object on Target Computer
column5: Try This Workaround

column3: Troubleshoot Cannot Load Shared Object on Target Computer
column5: These workarounds explore the possible issues.

column3: Troubleshoot Cannot Load Shared Object on Target Computer
column5: Check for Issues with Required Files

column3: Troubleshoot Cannot Load Shared Object on Target Computer
column5:
To check for this issue, connect to the target computer, and then try to build,
                load, and run example model slrt_ex_osc. If working with the
                default target computer, in the MATLAB® Command Window, type:

column3: Troubleshoot Cannot Load Shared Object on Target Computer
Troubleshoot Cannot Load Shared Object on Target Computer
column5:
If you can successfully connect to the target computer and build, load, and run
                the real-time application, there is no issue with files from the Simulink Real-Time
                Target Support Package on the target computer.

column3: Troubleshoot Cannot Load Shared Object on Target Computer
column5:
If you cannot complete those operations successfully, update the target computer
                software by using the force option. If working with the default
                target computer, in the MATLAB Command Window, type:

column3: Troubleshoot Cannot Load Shared Object on Target Computer
column5: update(tg,'force',true);

column3: Troubleshoot Cannot Load Shared Object on Target Computer
column5:
After the software update, connect to the target computer and try to build, load,
                and run the real-time application..

column3: Troubleshoot Cannot Load Shared Object on Target Computer
column5: Check Location of Shared Object on Target Computer

column3: Troubleshoot Cannot Load Shared Object on Target Computer
column5:
To check for this issue, use SSH or FTP to examine the location of the shared
                object file on the target computer. For more information, see Execute Target Computer RTOS Commands at Target Computer Command Line.

column3: Troubleshoot Cannot Load Shared Object on Target Computer
column5:
After you build the real-time application that links to a shared object, you must
                install the real-time application and the shared object on the target computer. Put
                the shared objects in a location on the target computer where they can be found and
                loaded at run time. The recommended locations are /lib,
                    /usr/lib, or /usr/local/lib. Root access
                is required to copy or modify files in these locations.
